<Article
  title="How to Appeal a Non-Renewal"
  seoTitle="How to Appeal a Homeowners Insurance Non-Renewal"
  description="You can sometimes contest a homeowners insurance non-renewal — but not always, and not the way most people expect. What actually works, what doesn't, and when to stop appealing and start shopping."
  pillar="non-renewed"
  lastUpdated="June 2026"
>

<p class="page-summary">A non-renewal can sometimes be contested, corrected, or paused — but an honest appeal starts with a hard question: do you have a factual error to fix, or are you asking an insurer to change a lawful business decision? Those are different fights, with very different odds. This page walks through which one you're in, how to run each, and when to stop appealing and start shopping instead.</p>

<section class="fast-answer">
  <h2>The Fast Answer</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"Appeal" means two different things.</strong> Fixing a factual error behind the decision (wrong claims history, wrong roof age, a mistaken wildfire score) is often winnable. Asking an insurer to reverse a lawful, risk-based decision to leave your ZIP code is usually not.</li>
    <li><strong>Get the real reason in writing first.</strong> You generally have a legal right to know why. If the decision used a consumer report or score, federal law (the Fair Credit Reporting Act) gives you an <strong>adverse action</strong> notice and a free copy of the report it relied on.</li>
    <li><strong>The state insurance department can investigate, but it can't usually force a renewal.</strong> A regulator can reverse an <em>unlawful</em> or improperly noticed non-renewal. It cannot order an insurer to keep insuring a risk it lawfully chose to drop.</li>
    <li><strong>California has specific tools others don't:</strong> a right to appeal your wildfire risk score directly to the insurer, and a one-year ban on non-renewals after a declared wildfire disaster.</li>
    <li><strong>Run the appeal and your replacement search at the same time.</strong> Appeals are slow and often fail. Never let the appeal become the reason your coverage lapses.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>First, Know Which Fight You're In</h2>

  <p>A <strong>non-renewal</strong> — your insurer declining to offer a new policy when your current one ends — is not the same as a <strong>cancellation</strong> (your insurer ending coverage mid-policy, which is allowed only for narrow reasons like nonpayment or fraud). The distinction matters for an appeal, because the two are governed by different rules. Cancellations are tightly restricted and frequently improper, which makes them more winnable. Non-renewals are broadly permitted: in most states an insurer can decline to renew almost any policy as long as it gives proper notice and isn't doing so for an illegal reason. For the full breakdown of what your letter is and isn't, start with <a href="/non-renewed/what-a-non-renewal-letter-actually-means/">what a non-renewal letter actually means</a>.</p>

  <p>So before you spend a week drafting an appeal, sort your situation into one of two buckets:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>A factual or procedural error.</strong> The decision rests on something that is wrong, or the insurer didn't follow the rules. Wrong claims on your record, a misread roof age, an inflated wildfire score, or a notice that arrived too late or without a stated reason. This is the winnable kind.</li>
    <li><strong>A lawful business decision.</strong> The insurer is reducing exposure in your area, your home's risk genuinely exceeds what it will write, or it's exiting the state. The facts are right; you simply don't like the conclusion. This is the kind that rarely reverses, no matter how well you write.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Most non-renewals in high-risk states are the second kind. That's not a reason to give up — it's a reason to aim your energy correctly. We'd rather you find replacement coverage than win a moral argument with an actuary.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Do You Actually Have a Case? A Decision Tree</h2>

  <p>Walk this top to bottom. The first "yes" tells you what kind of appeal you have — and whether it's worth your 30-day clock.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Ask yourself</th>
        <th>If yes</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Did the notice arrive with less than your state's required notice period (often 30–90 days), or with no stated reason?</td>
        <td><strong>Procedural challenge.</strong> File with your state insurance department — an improperly noticed non-renewal can be voided.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Does the stated reason rely on a claim, loss, or fact that is wrong or isn't yours?</td>
        <td><strong>Factual correction.</strong> Pull your CLUE report, dispute the error, ask the insurer to re-decide on corrected data.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Are you in California and is the reason a wildfire risk score?</td>
        <td><strong>Score appeal.</strong> You have a right to appeal that score directly to the insurer (see below).</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Was your area placed under a declared disaster (e.g. wildfire) within the last year?</td>
        <td><strong>Possible moratorium.</strong> A state ban on non-renewals may make the action unlawful right now (see below).</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Do you suspect the real reason is illegal (e.g. based on race, or retaliation for a question you asked)?</td>
        <td><strong>Regulatory complaint.</strong> This is exactly what the state DOI investigates.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>None of the above — the facts are right and the insurer is simply leaving?</td>
        <td><strong>Stop appealing. Start shopping.</strong> Your time is better spent on replacement coverage.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Step One: Get the Real Reason in Writing</h2>

  <p>You can't appeal a decision you don't understand, and the reason printed on the letter is often a generic phrase ("underwriting reasons," "risk profile"). <strong>Underwriting</strong> — the process an insurer uses to decide whether to cover a risk and at what price — runs on specific data, and you have rights to see it.</p>

  <p><strong>If the decision used a report or score, demand the adverse action notice.</strong> Under the federal Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA), when an insurer takes an <strong>adverse action</strong> (a denial, non-renewal, or less favorable terms) based on a consumer report, it must tell you, identify the reporting agency, and let you get a free copy of that report. Two reports drive most home-insurance decisions:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Your CLUE report</strong> — the Comprehensive Loss Underwriting Exchange, a national database of your property's insurance claims history. Order it free from LexisNexis. Errors here — a claim that wasn't yours, a closed-without-payment inquiry logged as a loss — are common and fixable, and they're a leading cause of non-renewals you can actually reverse.</li>
    <li><strong>Your credit-based insurance score</strong> — a score derived from your credit history that many insurers use in rating, where state law allows it. If a wrong credit entry hurt it, fixing the credit record can change the insurance outcome.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Put your request in writing and keep a copy. Ask the insurer, plainly: <em>what specific facts drove this decision, and what would I need to change for you to reconsider?</em> Sometimes the answer is concrete and fixable (a roof past a certain age, a missing wind-mitigation feature). Sometimes it's "we are no longer writing in your ZIP code," which is your signal that no appeal will land and you should pivot.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Step Two: Use the State Insurance Department — and Know Its Limits</h2>

  <p>Every state has an insurance department (the DOI, or in some states a Commissioner's office) with a consumer division that takes complaints for free. Filing one is worth doing in the right circumstances — and a waste of your clock in the wrong ones. Be clear-eyed about what it can and can't do.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>The state DOI <em>can</em></th>
        <th>The state DOI usually <em>cannot</em></th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Void a non-renewal that broke notice rules or stated no valid reason</td>
        <td>Order an insurer to renew a policy it lawfully chose to drop</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Investigate whether the reason was illegal or discriminatory</td>
        <td>Overrule a legitimate, risk-based underwriting judgment</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Force correction of data errors the insurer relied on</td>
        <td>Make an insurer write business in an area it's exiting</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Confirm whether a disaster moratorium protects you right now</td>
        <td>Set your premium or guarantee you a better quote elsewhere</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>This is the part most homeowners get wrong. As the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) frames it, regulators police whether a non-renewal was <em>lawful and properly handled</em> — not whether it was <em>kind</em>. A complaint that says "this is unfair, I've never had a claim" rarely moves anything. A complaint that says "the notice gave me 18 days when state law requires 45," or "this decision relied on a claim that belongs to the prior owner," gives the regulator a lever it can actually pull. Bring a specific, documented violation, or save the energy.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>California's Extra Tools</h2>

  <p>California gives homeowners two appeal mechanisms most states don't, both worth knowing if your non-renewal is wildfire-driven. (Our <a href="/is-my-zip-next/california/">California state page</a> covers the broader market.)</p>

  <p><strong>1. Appeal your wildfire risk score.</strong> Many insurers price and non-renew California homes using a <strong>wildfire risk score</strong> — a model-generated rating of your property's fire exposure. Under California regulation (10 CCR § 2644.9, the "Safer from Wildfires" framework), an insurer that uses such a score must disclose it on request and give you a right to appeal it directly to the insurer, in writing or orally, if you believe it's wrong. The insurer must return a revised score within 30 days. If your home has mitigation the model missed — a Class A roof, cleared defensible space, ember-resistant vents — documenting it through this appeal can lower the score that triggered the action. To understand which model your insurer likely used, see <a href="/is-my-zip-next/wildfire-score-vs-verisk-score-vs-corelogic-which-does-my-insurer-use/">wildfire score vs. Verisk score vs. CoreLogic</a>.</p>

  <p><strong>2. Check for a disaster moratorium.</strong> Under California Insurance Code § 675.1 (enacted by SB 824), once the Governor declares a wildfire emergency, insurers are barred from non-renewing or cancelling residential policies within the fire perimeter and adjoining ZIP codes for one year. A <strong>disaster moratorium</strong> — a temporary, state-ordered ban on non-renewals and cancellations in a disaster area — can make a non-renewal flatly unlawful for the duration. Homes that suffered a total loss get two additional annual renewals beyond the one year. The California Department of Insurance publishes the protected ZIP codes after each declaration; check whether yours is on the list before you do anything else. Several other wildfire and hurricane states have adopted narrower versions of this protection, so ask your DOI even outside California.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>The Honest Odds</h2>

  <p>We won't quote you an appeal "success rate," because no credible, current one exists — anyone who gives you a precise percentage is guessing. What the federal data does tell us is the shape of the problem. The U.S. Treasury Federal Insurance Office (FIO), January 2025 report — <em>Analyses of U.S. Homeowners Insurance Markets, 2018 to 2022: Climate-Related Risks and Other Factors</em> — documented insurers systematically withdrawing from the highest-risk ZIP codes, not making individualized judgments one home at a time. The U.S. Senate Budget Committee, December 2024 staff report — <em>"Next to Fall: The Climate-Driven Insurance Crisis Is Here and Getting Worse"</em> — described the same pattern: climate-driven retreat by whole markets, not isolated decisions an individual appeal can reverse.</p>

  <p>The practical takeaway: appeals that fix a <em>fact</em> have a real chance. Appeals that challenge a <em>strategy</em> almost never do. If your non-renewal is part of a carrier pulling out of your region — common right now in Florida, California, and Louisiana — the most likely outcome of an appeal is that you lose three weeks you needed for shopping. Win the fights you can win, and don't let the others cost you your safety net.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>When to Stop Appealing and Start Replacing</h2>

  <p>Pivot the moment the reason in writing turns out to be accurate and strategic rather than mistaken. At that point your job is continuous coverage, not vindication. The replacement ladder, roughly in order:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Shop the admitted market first</strong> — other standard carriers may still write your home, especially after you've corrected any data errors or added mitigation. Work the <a href="/non-renewed/your-30-60-90-day-decision-tree/">30-60-90 day decision tree</a> to sequence this.</li>
    <li><strong>Then surplus lines</strong> — non-admitted coverage built for hard-to-insure homes, with trade-offs worth understanding before you buy. See <a href="/non-renewed/how-surplus-lines-coverage-works/">how surplus lines coverage actually works</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Then your state's residual market</strong> — the FAIR Plan, Citizens, or equivalent insurer of last resort. Start at our <a href="/residual-markets/">Residual Markets</a> section.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Whatever you do, do not let coverage lapse — even for a day — while an appeal is pending. A gap can trigger force-placed insurance from your mortgage servicer at two to five times market rate, and in rare cases a technical loan default. See <a href="/non-renewed/will-my-mortgage-be-called/">will my mortgage be called?</a> for how that mechanism works. An imperfect policy bound on time always beats a perfect appeal that arrives after your old coverage ended.</p>
</section>

<section class="next-steps">
  <h2>What to Do in the Next 30 Days</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Request the specific reason in writing, plus any adverse action notice.</strong> Ask what facts drove the decision and what would change it. If a report or score was used, demand the FCRA notice and your free copy.</li>
    <li><strong>Pull your CLUE report from LexisNexis and check it for errors.</strong> Dispute anything wrong in writing. A corrected record is the single most common basis for a non-renewal that actually reverses.</li>
    <li><strong>Check for a disaster moratorium covering your ZIP code.</strong> If your area had a declared wildfire or other disaster in the past year, call your state DOI and confirm whether a non-renewal ban currently applies to you.</li>
    <li><strong>If you're in California and the reason is a wildfire score, file the score appeal — and document your mitigation.</strong> The insurer must return a revised score within 30 days; a Class A roof and defensible space can move it.</li>
    <li><strong>Start your replacement search now, in parallel with any appeal.</strong> Get at least one bindable quote in hand before your current policy's expiration date. Treat the appeal as upside, not as your plan.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

